@Composable
fun BrokenState() {
    // 1. State without remember
    var count = mutableStateOf(0)  // Resets on recomposition!

    // 2. Mutating state directly
    var name by remember { mutableStateOf("") }
    name = name + "a"  // This triggers recomposition, but inefficient

    // 3. State in non-Composable
    fun regularFunction() {
        var state by mutableStateOf(0)  // Error!
    }

    // 4. Forgetting to use by
    var count2 = remember { mutableStateOf(0) }
    Text("Count: ${count2.value}")  // Need .value

    // 5. State from multiple sources
    var text1 by remember { mutableStateOf("") }
    var text2 by remember { mutableStateOf("") }
    // Both cause recomposition independently
}

phase2.explanation:
рҹӨ– **Common state mistakes and how to fix them.**

| Mistake | Fix |
|---------|-----|
| State without remember | Use `remember { mutableStateOf() }` |
| Direct mutation | Use `by` delegate or `.value` |
| State in non-Composable | Only use in Composable |
| Forgetting `.value` | Use `by` delegate |
| Too many states | Use data class or combine |

**Fixes:**
```kotlin
// 1. Use remember
var count by remember { mutableStateOf(0) }

// 2. Use by delegate
var name by remember { mutableStateOf("") }
name = "new"

// 3. Only in Composable
@Composable
fun MyComposable() {
    var state by remember { mutableStateOf(0) }
}

// 4. Use by delegate
var count by remember { mutableStateOf(0) }
Text("Count: $count")

// 5. Combine states
data class UiState(val text1: String, val text2: String)
var uiState by remember { mutableStateOf(UiState("", "")) }
```

**Kotlin-chan says:**
"State is powerful but use it wisely. Keep it minimal and hoisted."

